<subSubSection id="50DBD8E27B248D50FF06442DA68AF8E1" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="187E8B697B248D50FF06442DA308F9A6" blockId="14.[189,310,1577,1603]" box="[189,310,1577,1603]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">
<heading id="43363C057B248D50FF06442DA308F9A6" bold="true" box="[189,310,1577,1603]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" reason="3">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FF06442DA308F9A6" bold="true" box="[189,310,1577,1603]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="187E8B697B248D50FF06445DA68AF8E1" blockId="14.[189,1399,1625,1797]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">
This species has the T1 mostly impunctate, the anterior surface of the mesoscutum not rugulose, and the metapostnotum trapezoidal. It is similar in size to 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B248D50FC85447AA1F8F972" authority="Gonçalves &amp; Pereira, 2022" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Pereira" authorityYear="2022" box="[830,966,1661,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerberus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FC85447AA171F97D" box="[830,847,1662,1688]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FCE44479A1F8F972" box="[863,966,1661,1687]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">cerberus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="3186EA007B248D50FC75447AA614F97D" box="[974,1066,1662,1688]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B248D50FBDD447AA6DBF972" authority="Gonçalves &amp; Pereira, 2022" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Pereira" authorityYear="2022" box="[1126,1253,1662,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tartarus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FBDD447AA649F97D" box="[1126,1143,1662,1688]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FB3D447AA6DBF972" box="[1158,1253,1662,1687]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">tartarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="3186EA007B248D50FB56447AA777F97D" box="[1261,1353,1662,1688]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
but the head is not enlarged and the mesoscutum is not sulcate. Differently from 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B248D50FBE944A6A6D9F95E" authority="Gonçalves &amp; Pereira, 2022" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Pereira" authorityYear="2022" box="[1106,1255,1697,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asmodeus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FBE944A6A65DF959" box="[1106,1123,1698,1724]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FBC844A5A6D9F95E" box="[1139,1255,1697,1723]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">asmodeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="3186EA007B248D50FB5444A6A775F959" box="[1263,1355,1698,1724]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the body length is more than 
<quantity id="DF39268C7B248D50FE5344C2A011F905" box="[488,559,1734,1760]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
, the anterior surface of the mesoscutum is sparsely punctate (i=pd), the scutellum has a well-defined longitudinal row of punctures, and the terga are lineolate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="50DBD8E27B248D50FF064528A6A5F892" box="[189,1179,1836,1911]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" type="description">
<paragraph id="187E8B697B248D50FF064528A30DF8A3" blockId="14.[189,307,1836,1862]" box="[189,307,1836,1862]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">
<heading id="43363C057B248D50FF064528A30DF8A3" bold="true" box="[189,307,1836,1862]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" reason="3">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FF064528A30DF8A3" bold="true" box="[189,307,1836,1862]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">Variation</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="187E8B697B248D50FF064558A6A5F892" blockId="14.[189,1179,1884,1911]" box="[189,1179,1884,1911]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">
Variation in body size was found in females, from 7.0 mm to 
<quantity id="DF39268C7B248D50FC364558A1D9F892" box="[909,999,1884,1911]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" unit="mm" value="8.5">8.5 mm</quantity>
(the 
<typeStatus id="C77A35CB7B248D50FB984558A6B1F892" box="[1059,1167,1884,1911]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">holotype</typeStatus>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="50DBD8E27B248D50FF06459BA707F80D" box="[189,1337,1951,2025]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="187E8B697B248D50FF06459BA37AF85C" blockId="14.[189,324,1951,1977]" box="[189,324,1951,1977]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">
<heading id="43363C057B248D50FF06459BA37AF85C" bold="true" box="[189,324,1951,1977]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="14" pageNumber="69" reason="3">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B248D50FF06459BA37AF85C" bold="true" box="[189,324,1951,1977]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="187E8B697B248D50FF0645CBA707F80D" blockId="14.[189,1337,1998,2025]" box="[189,1337,1998,2025]" pageId="14" pageNumber="69">From Greek mythology, grim, dreadful creature. The name is used as a proper noun in apposition.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
